      <h2>Composite Toe: The Modern Alternative</h2>
      <p>Composite toe caps are made from non-metal materials such as Kevlar, carbon fiber, fiberglass, or high-impact plastic. They meet the same ASTM ratings as steel while offering several unique advantages.</p>
      <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lighter than steel.</strong> Composite toes typically weigh 30–50% less than steel equivalents. This reduces foot fatigue significantly on long shifts.</li>
        <li><strong>Non-conductive.</strong> Composite materials don't conduct heat, cold, or electricity. This makes them the safest choice for electrical work and comfortable in extreme temperatures.</li>
        <li><strong>Metal-detector friendly.</strong> Won't trigger security sensors — useful for tradespeople who travel through airport security or work on secure sites.</li>
        <li><strong>No thermal transfer.</strong> Your toes stay warmer in winter and cooler in summer compared to steel-toe boots.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Bulkier toe box.</strong> Composite caps need to be thicker than steel to achieve the same strength. This can make the toe area feel roomier — some people love this, others find it clunky.</li>
        <li><strong>Less impact energy absorption at extremes.</strong> While both pass ASTM standards, composite caps can shatter under extreme impact that would dent a steel cap. This is rarely a practical concern since both meet the same 75 foot-pound standard.</li>
        <li><strong>More expensive.</strong> Composite toe boots typically cost $20–$50 more than equivalent steel-toe models.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Electricians, cold-weather workers, airport jobsite workers, and anyone who prioritizes lightweight comfort.</p>

