      <h2>Alloy Toe: The Lightest Option</h2>
      <p>Alloy toe caps use thin-gauge metals like titanium or aluminum. They're designed to offer the strength of steel with significantly less weight.</p>
      <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lightest of all three.</strong> Alloy toe caps can be 50% lighter than steel while providing the same ASTM protection.</li>
        <li><strong>Thin profile.</strong> Like steel, alloy caps are thin, so the toe box doesn't feel bulky — unlike composite toes.</li>
        <li><strong>No thermal conductivity issue.</strong> Some alloys (especially titanium) don't conduct cold as aggressively as steel, though they still conduct more than composite.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Most expensive.</strong> Alloy toe boots are at the premium end of the price spectrum.</li>
        <li><strong>Still metal.</strong> Alloy toes can conduct electricity (unless specifically EH-rated) and still trigger metal detectors, though less sensitively than steel.</li>
        <li><strong>Harder to find.</strong> Alloy toe boots are less common than steel or composite, especially at lower price points.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Experienced tradespeople who want the absolute lightest safety toe and are willing to pay a premium.</p>

